oc:kn_03f55d01 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When starting a new agent design" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Select agent type based on complexity: reactive (single-turn, no memory), conversational (multi-turn with memory), tool-using (external API calls), reasoning (multi-step planning), or multi-agent (specialized collaborating agents)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Over-engineering an agent adds unnecessary complexity; matching type to use case ensures appropriate capability without waste." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_2f2e9d70 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining tool/function calling interfaces" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Define tools using a structured schema with name, description, parameter types (including required vs optional), and implementation details (API endpoint, method, params)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clear tool schemas enable reliable function calling by the LLM and reduce hallucinated or malformed tool invocations." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_42d39d05 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing agent memory systems" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Choose memory type based on conversation needs: buffer memory (last N messages) for simple chatbots, summary memory for long conversations, vector memory for knowledge retrieval, entity memory for personalized assistants." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Memory type directly impacts context quality, token usage, and response relevance; wrong choice leads to lost context or excessive costs." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_5a172c77 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing agents that require multi-step reasoning" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the ReAct pattern (Thought → Action → Observation loop) for multi-step reasoning, or a Planning Agent approach (plan → execute each step → synthesize) for complex tasks." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Structured reasoning patterns prevent agents from getting stuck in loops and make debugging and tracing agent behavior easier." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_665a3557 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing customer-facing agents" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never build an agent without escalation triggers for human handoff — include sentiment detection, keyword matching, and failed resolution thresholds." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Agents without escalation paths can frustrate users and damage brand trust when they cannot resolve issues." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_6fa1f42a a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:directiveContent """# {Agent Name} Design

## Architecture
```yaml
agent:
  name: "{name}"
  model: {model}
  capabilities: [{list}]
```

## Tools Required
1. **{tool_name}** - Input: {inputs}, Output: {outputs}

## Conversation Flow
```
User: {sample_input}
Agent: [Thought: {reasoning}]
Agent: {sample_response}
```""" ;
    oc:hasRationale "This output format provides a complete agent design document that developers can directly implement." ;
    oc:templateVariables "Agent Name",
        "inputs",
        "list",
        "model",
        "name",
        "outputs",
        "reasoning",
        "sample_input",
        "sample_response",
        "tool_name" .

oc:kn_6fd9e3c9 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When managing context windows" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Allocate context window tokens with a budget: system prompt, tools, memory, current query, and response each get defined token limits that sum to the model's total." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without token budgets, an agent can exceed context limits causing truncation, degraded performance, or API errors." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_9eb4238e a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When integrating agents with messaging platforms" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For platform integrations (Slack, Telegram, Web), design agents with platform-specific trigger handling, context retrieval (e.g., thread history for Slack), tool selection per platform, and appropriate response formatting." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Each platform has unique message formats, context mechanisms, and user expectations that require tailored integration patterns." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_b01bf7f2 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Identify agent type (reactive/conversational/tool-using/reasoning/multi-agent) based on use case. 2. Define required tools with structured schemas. 3. Select memory pattern matching conversation needs. 4. Design reasoning approach (ReAct or Planning). 5. Implement platform integration with trigger handling. 6. Add escalation triggers for edge cases. 7. Configure context window token budget." ;
    oc:hasRationale "This sequence ensures all architectural decisions are made before implementation, reducing rework." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_bd7c9ca9 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing any AI agent" ;
    oc:directiveContent "An AI agent architecture consists of five core components: Input (Query), Agent (LLM), Output (Response), and three subsystems — Tools (Functions), Memory (Context), and Knowledge (RAG)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "This decomposition ensures all critical agent capabilities are addressed and provides a common vocabulary for agent design discussions." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_c29ddef6 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When defining any tool for an AI agent" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "yaml" ;
    oc:directiveContent """tool_definition:
  name: "{tool_name}"
  description: "{what_it_does}"
  parameters:
    type: object
    properties:
      {param_name}:
        type: string
        description: "{param_desc}"
    required: ["{required_params}"]
  implementation:
    type: api_call
    endpoint: "{api_url}"
    method: GET""" ;
    oc:hasRationale "A consistent tool definition schema ensures the LLM can correctly parse and invoke tools across all agent implementations." .

